"Abstract Data controllers have been very busy of late, keeping up with all the recent developments and guidance relating to (and the controversy surrounding) data protection. How to respond to data subject access requests (under section 7 of the Data Protection Act 1998 (“the Act”)), including knowing what is “personal data” and knowing when you are obliged to disclose it (and indeed not to disclose it), is no easy matter. Data controllers will therefore welcome the guidance offered in the recent case of David Johnson v The Medical Defence Union Limited [2004] EWHC 347 (20 February 2004)."
